Title:
ACS Central on 4.7 - Guidance Required to Upgrade to Support Secured Cluster 4.10 Without Downtime
Description:
Hi Team,
We are currently working on onboarding multiple OpenShift clusters into Red Hat Advanced Cluster Security (ACS).
Our current setup:
ACS Central is deployed using operator version 4.7
We are trying to import a secured cluster running ACS operator version 4.10
There is a version mismatch between Central and Secured Cluster components
We also already have multiple clusters successfully connected to the existing Central instance.
Issues / Concerns:
We understand that ACS components should be on compatible versions, and Central should typically be at the same or higher version than Secured Clusters.
We want to upgrade ACS Central from 4.7 to a supported version (e.g., 4.10 or later).
We need guidance on performing this upgrade:
Without downtime (or minimal downtime)
Without impacting already connected secured clusters
We also want to understand:
Whether existing secured clusters require upgrades after Central upgrade
If there is any recommended upgrade sequence (Central → Secured Clusters or vice versa)
Questions:
What is the recommended upgrade path from ACS 4.7 → 4.10 (or latest)?
Can this upgrade be performed without downtime for Central and connected clusters?
Will existing secured clusters continue to function during the Central upgrade?
Are there any pre-checks or prerequisites we should validate before upgrading?
After upgrading Central, do we need to manually upgrade all secured cluster services?
Is there any impact on policies, integrations, or sensors during upgrade?
